05116nam a22007815i 9780231552592DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020009243  a97802315525927 a10.7312/mors198362doi  a(DE-B1597)566372  a(OCoLC)1147932992  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1991.8.L5 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.90935582231 aMorse, Daniel Ryan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRadio Empire :bThe BBC’s Eastern Service and the Emergence of the Global Anglophone Novel /cDaniel Ryan Morse. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModernist Latitudes00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One Finnegans Waves -- tChapter Two Reviewing Some Books -- tChapter Three The End of Empire -- tChapter Four Intimate and Kaleidosonic Styles -- tEpilogue -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInitially created to counteract broadcasts from Nazi Germany, the BBC’s Eastern Service became a cauldron of global modernism and an unlikely nexus of artistic exchange. Directed at an educated Indian audience, its programming provided remarkable moments: Listeners in India heard James Joyce reading from Finnegans Wake on the eve of independence, as well as the literary criticism of E. M. Forster and the works of Indian writers living in London.In Radio Empire, Daniel Ryan Morse demonstrates the significance of the Eastern Service for global Anglophone literature and literary broadcasting. He traces how modernist writers used radio to experiment with form and introduce postcolonial literature to global audiences. While innovative authors consciously sought to incorporate radio’s formal features into the novel, literature also exerted a reciprocal and profound influence on twentieth-century broadcasting. Reading Joyce and Forster alongside Attia Hosain, Mulk Raj Anand, and Venu Chitale, Morse demonstrates how the need to appeal to listeners at the edges of the empire pushed the boundaries of literary work in London, inspired high-cultural broadcasting in England, and formed an invisible but influential global network.Adding a transnational perspective to scholarship on radio modernism, Radio Empire demonstrates how the history of broadcasting outside of Western Europe offers a new understanding of the relationship between colonial center and periphery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictionzForeign countriesxHistory and crticism. 0aRadio and literaturezGreat Britain. 0aRadio broadcasting, BritishxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mors1983640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231552592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231552592/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cul